#tuples are immutable data structures in python. Once a tuple is created, its elements cannot be modified, added, or removed. Tuples are defined using parentheses () and can contain elements of different data types.
#tuples are useful when you want to group related data together and ensure that the data remains unchanged throughout the program. They are often used to represent fixed collections of values, such as coordinates, RGB color values, or database records.
#tuples are unordered, meaning that the order of elements in a tuple does not matter. However, they can be indexed and sliced just like lists.

names=("John","Doe","Khalid","Indi",False,12,90.5) # tuple of names
print(names)
print(type(names)) # to check the type of variable we use type() function
print(type(names[5])) # to check the type of variable we use type() function
print(len(names)) # to check the length of the tuple
print(names[1]) # to print the second element of the tuple
print(names[0:3]) # to print the first three elements of the tuple
print(names.index("Khalid")) # to find the index of an element in the tuple
print(names.count("Khalid")) # to count the number of occurrences of an element in the tuple
print("Doe" in names) # to check whether an element is present in the tuple or not
print(sum([12,90.5])) # to find the sum of the elements in the tuple
